  <!-- Chapter 1 -->
  <div id="chapter1" class="chapter">
    <h2>‚ö° Chapter 1: Electric Charges and Fields (Physics)</h2>
    <p>Electric charge is a fundamental property of matter which causes it to experience a force when placed in an electric and magnetic field.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><span class="important">Coulomb‚Äôs Law:</span> The electrostatic force between two point charges is directly proportional to the product of charges and inversely proportional to the square of distance.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Electric Field:</span> Region around a charge where another charge experiences a force.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Electric Dipole:</span> Two equal and opposite charges separated by a small distance.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Applications:</span> Capacitors, photocopiers, and Van de Graaff generators.</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2d/Electric_Field_Lines.svg" alt="Electric Field Lines Diagram">
  </div>

  <!-- Chapter 2 -->
  <div id="chapter2" class="chapter">
    <h2>üß™ Chapter 2: Solid State (Chemistry)</h2>
    <p>Solids are rigid and have definite shape and volume. Intermolecular forces are strongest in solids.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><span class="important">Types of Solids:</span> Crystalline (ordered structure) and Amorphous (irregular structure).</li>
      <li><span class="important">Unit Cell:</span> Smallest repeating structure in a crystal lattice.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Packing Efficiency:</span> BCC < FCC < HCP arrangements.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Defects:</span> Schottky Defect (missing ions) and Frenkel Defect (displaced ions).</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/90/Cubic-body-centered-unit-cell-3D-balls.png" alt="Solid State Structure Diagram">
  </div>

  <!-- Chapter 3 -->
  <div id="chapter3" class="chapter">
    <h2>üß¨ Chapter 3: Human Reproduction (Biology)</h2>
    <p>The process by which a new individual of the same species is produced involving the union of male and female gametes.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><span class="important">Male System:</span> Testes, vas deferens, urethra, penis.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Female System:</span> Ovaries, fallopian tubes, uterus, vagina.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Important Events:</span> Gametogenesis, fertilization, implantation, parturition.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Hormones:</span> FSH, LH, Estrogen, Progesterone.</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4e/Human_Reproductive_System.png" alt="Human Reproductive System Diagram">
  </div>

  <!-- Chapter 4 -->
  <div id="chapter4" class="chapter">
    <h2>üå∏ Chapter 4: Sexual Reproduction in Flowering Plants (Biology)</h2>
    <p>Reproduction in flowering plants involves complex biological processes starting from pollination to seed development.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><span class="important">Pollination:</span> Transfer of pollen grains from anther to stigma.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Double Fertilization:</span> Unique feature of angiosperms where one sperm fertilizes egg and another forms endosperm.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Seed Development:</span> Ovule develops into seed, ovary develops into fruit.</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/Double_fertilization_diagram.png" alt="Double Fertilization Diagram">
  </div>

  <!-- Chapter 5 -->
  <div id="chapter5" class="chapter">
    <h2>üîã Chapter 5: Current Electricity (Physics)</h2>
    <p>Electric current is the flow of electric charge (generally electrons) in a conductor like metal wire.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><span class="important">Ohm‚Äôs Law:</span> V = IR (Voltage = Current √ó Resistance)</li>
      <li><span class="important">Resistivity:</span> Property of material affecting resistance (constant for given material).</li>
      <li><span class="important">Series and Parallel Circuits:</span> Different ways of connecting resistors.</li>
      <li><span class="important">Kirchhoff's Laws:</span> Used for analyzing complex circuits.</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/28/Simple_circuit_diagram.png" alt="Simple Circuit Diagram">
  </div>

